MissionCommands.Message: Welcome onboard on Apollo 13, where the journey towards the Moon continues as the crew prepares for the T&D maneuver.
13, Houston.
Roger, Houston; 13 here.
Okay. We have the S-IVB maneuver to Sep attitude commencing at 2 plus 56 plus 37. Duration of the maneuver: 4 minutes. Sep time, 3 plus 06 plus 37. Over.
Okay. If I heard those right, Joe, that the S-IVB maneuver was 2 plus 56 plus 57, and Sep time is 3 plus 06 plus 27.
Correction on the seconds; 2 plus 56 plus 37, and 3 plus 06 plus 37.
Okay. 2 plus 56 plus 37 with the maneuver time; and the Sep time, 3 plus 06 plus 27?
That's plus 37, too. Exactly 10 minutes later, Fred.
Okay; 37.
Ok, let us start with the PRE CSM SEPARATION checklist. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > PRE CSM SEPARATION[1] checklist]
Roger, starting checklist.
Apollo 13, Houston.
Go ahead.

We see the booster doing all the right things, and FIDO says your trajectory looks good, and it looks like we'll stick with a pretty close to nominal midcourse, too. We'll have some numbers for you later.
Okay. And we concur. The S-IVB is maneuvering at this time.
If not complete, complete the PRE CSM SEPARATION checklist
And, Apollo 13, Houston. We'd like Omni Alpha. Over.
Omni Alpha, coming up.
13, Houston. Now request Omni Charlie.
Roger. Going Charlie.
And, 13, we'll be doing a handover, now.
Okay
Apollo 13, Houston. You are Go for T&D.
Okay, Joe. Thank you.
Ok, separation comming up at 3 plus 06 plus 37, let us prepare the CSM. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > CSM SEPARATION PREP [2] checklist]
Roger, completing the checklist.
Okay, checklist complete.
Okay, then start the CSM SEPARATION checklist, complete the steps until pyro arm.
Okay, Houston; 13. Do we have a Go for pyro arm?
13, Houston. Affirmative. You're Go for pyro arm, and recommend you secure the cabin pressurization.
We did. We closed the waste management vent valve, there. Or waste stowage valves...
Okay. We're reading 6 psi on the cabin, Jack.
Roger, Joe. Thank you very much.
Ok, prepare for separation at 3 plus 06 plus 37. [Follow the checklist and event timer]
Ok, 30 seconds to sep. Make sure to start the DET counting up from 59:30 - follow the checklist and stage on time.
Yeah, that's quite a bang, Joe. We've separated.
Roger, Jack. We see you.
Okay. We got the SLA panels; one of them is out front now.
As you might know, Joe, I've got the center seat, again and I can't see a thing.
Too bad.
[When you are lined up with the SIVB after the 180 degrees turnaround, complete the checklist]
Ok, CSM Separation checklist complete, continue with the Docking checklist. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > DOCKING [4] checklist]
Ok, will line up and dock this. [Keep focus and follow the checklist to dock with the LM/SIVB]
Okay. We've - we've got two barber poles.
Houston; Roger.
Okay. You should be able to see down into the portion of the IU right now, Joe.
Will complete the checklist.
We're hard docked, Houston.
Roger. Understand. Hard docked. Good deal.
And, Houston, Fred will handle the camera as we go through the postdocking checklist. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > POST DOCKING [5] checklist]
Okay, Jim. Real good. [Complete the checklist]
And we have word that the propellant usage for T&D was nominal.
Okay, what is nominal, please?
Well, I didn't ask that yet, Jack; stand by one.
Haha, that's okay.
Houston, we're now going to finish repressurizing the tunnel.
Houston; Roger.
[RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > CM/LM PRESSURE EQ [6] checklist]
Joe, we're just finishing pumping up Aquarius here. [Complete the checklist]
Ok, then its the tunnel hatch removal. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > TUNNEL HATCH REMOVAL [7] checklist]
Ok, complete the checklist.
What you're looking at, Joe, is the commander has removed the hatch and is proceeding to stow it.
The CDR is verifying the docking latches now.
Hey, Joe. Jim reports that there's a slight, you know, burn smell up in the tunnel area, as been reported on previous flights.
Okay. We copy that.
Okay. The commander reports all docking latches latched.
Houston; Roger.
Ok, then it's the umbilical, let me get it connected right away. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > LM UMBILICAL CONNECTION [9] checklist]
13. Looks like Jim is connecting the umbilical at this time. Is that right?
Yeah, that's affirm - affirm, Joe.
Okay. We're powering the LM now, Joe.
Okay, roger that. [Complete the checklist]
And the voltage looks good there, 13.
Roger.
Okay. Getting ready for LM extraction. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > PRE LM SEP & EJECTION [11] checklist]
Houston, this is 13. Do we have a Go for pyro arm?
13, Houston. Affirmative. You're Go for pyro arm. [Complete the checklist]
Okay, 13; Houston. You're Go for LM SEP whenever you're ready.
Roger.
Okay, 13; Houston. Correction on that. You're Go for LM SEP at the nominal time and - or later. We don't want it early.
Okay, Joe. We'll do it at 04:01:00.
Roger.
Okay. We're about ready to pull the LM out, Joe. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > LM SEP & EJECTION [12] and separate at ~04:01:00]
Okay, 13. [Complete the checklist]
Here she comes.
Okay. It looks like we're clear, Joe.
Okay. Looks good.
Ok, post LM separation procedures. [RUN the TIMELINE -> T&D > POST LM EJECTION [13] checklist]
Okay, completing the checklist.
Apollo 13, Houston.
Go ahead.
Okay. We'll be waiting for you to tell us that you feel you're safely clear of the booster, and give us the Go to command the booster in its yaw maneuver.
13, Houston. Did you - did you copy my last about giving us a Go for the yaw?
Yeah, we're maneuvering, Joe, and we hadn't picked her back up again yet.
Okay. Do you want to wait till you acquire it before we yaw it?
How much time do you have, Houston? Can you wait, or do you want to do it right now?
We can wait if you want us to, Jim.
Why don't you wait just a little bit.
Okay.
Joe, did they ever get an idea of what that - the TD and E fuel was?
Jack, they're not willing to pin it down to a specific number right now because they say the tanks will warm up later on and the apparent consumption will go down. But it was nominal.
Okay.
Ok, center the SIVB booster in the CDR or Hatch window and keep it there. Press [I SEE IT] when you have it in sight.
Okay, Houston. We have the S-IVB in sight. You're Go to maneuver the S-IVB.
Houston, Roger that.
Okay, it is yawing.
Roger, Jim. We copy that. Incidentally, the APS evasive maneuver will be about 4 minutes late. It'll be at about 04 plus 18.
Roger.
And, 13, Houston. We'll be commanding the evasive maneuver in about 17 seconds.
Okay, Joe. We can see it start to move. However, it doesn't seem to be a lot of debris or vapor coming out of it.
Roger that, Jack. Booster says that's great. He says the booster's doing its thing normally. Concur. We don't see much on the television at all.
And, 13, Houston. The APS evasive maneuver appeared to be nominal. The LOX dump time is now 4 plus 39 plus 20, about 3 minutes late.
Roger.
Ok, next up on the flight plan is to charge battery B. [RUN the COMMAND MODULE -> SYSTEMS: EPS > BATTERY CHARGING checklist with BATTERY B as the target battery]
[Ok, then complete the checks until BATTERY B is charging, then press CLEAR to complete the checklist]
Okay, Houston. We're charging battery B.
Roger, 13. We see it. Looks good.

The booster engineer reports the preliminary indications are that our Saturn S-IVB evasive maneuver was successful. The Flight Dynamics Officer will be evaluating the trajectory to assure that we've got the kind of separation from the spacecraft that we were looking for and also to determine to what extent we are heading toward the trajectory which would impact the S-IVB on the Moon.

At 6 pm Central Standard Time, there will be a press conference in the news center auditorium. This is the small auditorium in Building 1, with Ken Mattingly. Astronaut Mattingly, until a few days ago, was the prime Command Module Pilot for the mission and due to exposure to measles, was replaced by Jack Swigert.

Mattingly has been in the control center and is currently in the control center observing the progress of the mission. I have to repeat that press conference with astronaut Mattingly is scheduled for 6 pm Central Standard Time in the news center auditorium.
[This completes the mission, the journey continues in the next mission]

Title: MISSION 4 - T&D
Description: After a successful TLI burn, Apollo 13 is on a lunar trajectory. The crew will need to separate from the SIVB, execute the turn around maneuver, dock with the Lunar Module and extract it from the SIVB.
BriefingText:
Primary objectives:
• to perform selenological inspection, survey, and sampling of
materials in a preselected region of the Fra Mauro formation;
• to deploy and activate an Apollo lunar surface experiments package;
• to further develop human capability to work in the lunar environment; and
• to obtain photographs of candidate exploration sites.

Transposition, Docking & Extraction:
- Separation time: 003:06:37.
- Separation attitude: 358°, 139°, 320° in roll, pitch and yaw.
- Extraction attitude: 302°, 319°, 40° in roll, pitch and yaw.
- Ejection time: 004:01:00.
